{"id":"2002.12643","submitter":"Taoyang Wu","authors":"Kwok Pui Choi and Ariadne Thompson and Taoyang Wu","title":"On cherry and pitchfork distributions of random rooted and unrooted\n  phylogenetic trees","comments":"26 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR math.CO q-bio.PE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Tree shape statistics are important for investigating evolutionary mechanisms\nmediating phylogenetic trees. As a step towards bridging shape statistics\nbetween rooted and unrooted trees, we present a comparison study on two subtree\nstatistics known as numbers of cherries and pitchforks for the proportional to\ndistinguishable arrangements (PDA) and the Yule-Harding-Kingman (YHK) models.\nBased on recursive formulas on the joint distribution of the number of cherries\nand that of pitchforks, it is shown that cherry distributions are log-concave\nfor both rooted and unrooted trees under these two models. Furthermore, the\nmean number of cherries and that of pitchforks for unrooted trees converge\nrespectively to those for rooted trees under the YHK model while there exists a\nlimiting gap of 1/4 for the PDA model. Finally, the total variation distances\nbetween the cherry distributions of rooted and those of unrooted trees converge\nfor both models. Our results indicate that caution is required for conducting\nstatistical analysis for tree shapes involving both rooted and unrooted trees.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 28 Feb 2020 10:37:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-03-02"}
