{"id":"2002.12802","submitter":"Benjamin Favier","authors":"Benjamin Favier and Edgar Knobloch","title":"Robust wall states in rapidly rotating Rayleigh-B\\'enard convection","comments":"14 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We show, using direct numerical simulations with experimentally realizable\nboundary conditions, that wall modes in Rayleigh-B\\'enard convection in a\nrapidly rotating cylinder persist even very far from their linear onset. These\nnonlinear wall states survive in the presence of turbulence in the bulk and are\nrobust with respect to changes in the shape of the boundary of the container.\nIn this sense these modes behave much like the topologically protected states\npresent in two-dimensional chiral systems even though rotating convection is a\nthree-dimensional nonlinear driven dissipative system. We suggest that the\nrobustness of this nonlinear mode may provide an explanation for the strong\nzonal flows observed recently in simulations and experiments on rapidly\nrotating convection at high Rayleigh number.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 28 Feb 2020 15:27:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 27 Apr 2020 14:48:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-28"}
